text: "Patient with 3 COVID vaccines who admitted to hospital with COVID detected PCR.  Provider d/c note:  ""72yo female with hx of COPD, chronic hypoxic respiratory failure, anxiety, bipolar disease, CAD s/p stent, HTN, HLD, hx of seizures who reported to Hospital ED with acute complaint of shortness of breath. At home, patient uses supplemental oxygen at 1L per which she required an increase in supplemental O2. She was developing worsening chronic cough with productive sputum. Reported generalized fatigue prior to arrival. She denied fever, chills, rigors, orthopnea. Patient took a home COVID test which was positive on 10/21/22.    In the ED, patient was afebrile and hemodynamically stable. SpO2 2was 96% on 2L. She initially was found to have increased work of breathing and placed on BiPAP. She became hypotensive to 87/35, fluids were administered. Patient received Ativan and was transitioned to CPAP from BiPAP. WBC was 16.2, COVID was positive. Chest XR remarkable for bibasilar reticulonodular opacities.    Hospital Course:  Patient was taken off BiPAP, started on Decadron and Remdesivir for COVID pneumonia. IV rocephin and doxycycline were started for COPD exacerbation. Patient's hyponatremia resolved with fluids. Patient complained of multiple episodes of loose stools. C. Diff isolation and testing protocols were initiated on 10/25/22, with negative results. Patient's loose stools improved with PRN imodium. Blood cultures continued to show no growth. She was discharged in stable condition to home with home-care after completing Remdesivir therapy and 5 days of antibiotics.   Issues Requiring Follow Up: (Who, what, when, and how communicated?) PCP - COPD exacerbation and COVID pneumonia f/u. Discharged with short course Decadron to complete 10 days therapy."""
labels: Diarrhoea, Dyspnoea, 19, Productive cough, Positive airway pressure therapy, Hypotension, Condition aggravated, 19 pneumonia, Fatigue, SARS, Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, Lung opacity, Hyponatraemia, ray abnormal, Blood culture negative

text: 17 year old male with no significant past medical history who presents with chest pain and elevated troponins following his second Covid vaccination. He received the dose 11/3/21.  After his vaccine, he had flu-like symptoms, similar to after his first dose. On 11/6, he felt mild SOB in the afternoon without associated pain.  Later that night at 0100 the morning of admission, he experienced left sided, non-radiating, sharp pleuritic chest pain.  Taking deep breaths made the pain worse and there was nothing he could do to make the pain better. He experienced no nausea, vomiting, numbness, tingling, jaw claudication, or diaphoresis. He does admit to tender lymph nodes in his left axilla, which he also had after his first dose of the vaccine.   He presented to an outside emergency room this morning. At that time he was found to have tachycardia, with an EKG notable only for sinus tachycardia. Troponin was elevated at that time. Due to concerns for myocarditis, he was transferred to our facility for echo evaluation, which showed good function. His pain also improved. As such, he was admitted for ongoing monitoring.

text: 22 y/o male who collapsed after a prolonged high intensity exercise run wearing about 30-40 lbs of gear on field run for > 1 hour; felt "unwell" at the end of 4 mile run; walked around about 1 1/2 laps and then collapsed. Does not recall any events following collapse until about 8 days later while hospitalized. Pt felt well prior to run - "near 100%". Reports he was well hydrated. When patient transported by ambulance, he experienced an altered mental status (initially unresponsive, then agitated, combative) and his temperature was 109 degrees F, rectally, which was confirmed at ER as >107 degrees F, rectally. Efforts to cool and sedate (received ATIVAN and HALDOL --> intubated). Temp down to 103 degrees F --> transferred to another Hospital. Temp down to 101 on admission; given additional fentanyl and versed for agitation. Hemodynamically stable with HRs 80-90 and SBP 100-20s; O2 stats > 97%. Loose green stools. HOSPITAL COURSE: Agitated, febrile to 102 rectally despite cooling blanket, fan and ice packs. Given Librium d/t concern for DTs with ETOH intake of about 30 beers/week (last ETOH intake around 3/14/2010); given VERSED as needed for agitation. Concern for cerebral edema (per CT with concern for herniation; episode in scanner where he was unresponsive, sluggish small pupils, heart rate in 30s, requiring resuscitation -->MICU). Given Mannitol with improvement. F/u MRI w/o evidence of elevated ICP. Received coverage for infections (doxy, vancomycin, ceftriaxzone, and acyclovir). After consultation with CDC and VHC, VIG (X1) administered IV (6000 units per kg) and pat also received IV methylprednisolone. Over hospital course, temperature returned to normal after several days, LFTS improved and mental status improved to near baseline. By 24 March, patient was extubated. He was following commands and answering questions, but no recall of previous 7 days. He was discharged on 28 March 2010. 13 April, Follow up visit, problems with motor skills (difficulty using fork and pen) and continues to report memory lapses ( -- > repair MRI and Neurology follow-up appt). 26 April, Follow Up, problems with mild memory lapses with forgetting what he is doing and at time how to do simple things such as tie his shoes. Problems falling asleep with sleep initiation taking anywhere from 2-3 hours. Also, admits to increased mood swings but he admits to being under some pressure from all this going on.

text: 4 month old daughter was given 4 month vaccinations, including the oral ROTATEQ on Wed 1/4. On the morning of Fri 1/6 she developed a fever and rash that lasted for over a week. Her pediatrician could not determine cause of illness. Other symptoms began to show-diarrhea, vomiting, lethargy, red eyes, swollen cracked lips, red swollen soles of feet. Fever, rash and other symptoms lasted for 13 days. Finally on 1/20 her doctor diagnosed her with Kawasakis disease and she was admitted to the hospital on the same day. She was given an IVIG and high doses of aspirin to treat the illness. We believe there is a correlation between receiving the ROTATEQ and her development of fever and rash and ultimately Kawasaki disease. She was healthy on the day of receiving her vaccinations and became ill less than 48 hours after receiving the oral vaccination. She also received vaccinations for PENTACEL and pneumococcal conjugate, ped. 7 valent.

text: About 12 hours after the shot I had rolling chills, chattering teeth, bone pain, muscle aches, and felt poorly. At around the 14 hour mark, I got debilitating nausea and a fever that reached 102.1. I vomited from about 12am-3:30am solid. I was able to go to sleep around 5, awoke at 7 with pain and nausea again, took a Tylenol, and was able to go back to sleep. I slept until 2:30pm. I still had joint and bone aches and a bad headache and a lower fever of about 101. That dissipated throughout the evening (Tuesday evening). Wednesday I felt a bit better aside from a very sore neck and headache. I took another 1000 mg of Tylenol on Wednesday. Today (Thursday), I woke up with pretty significant vertigo. I have placed a call to my primary care provider. I still have some lingering neck pain as well.
labels: Bone pain, Vertigo, Neck pain, Pyrexia, Myalgia, Vomiting, Feeling abnormal, Headache, Arthralgia, Nausea, Chills, Sleep disorder

text: About thirty minutes after getting my booster I started getting a sore arm. About mid afternoon I was feeling body aches. By 4:00PM I was having chills and severe body aches. Around 9-10PM I had a horrible headache that lasted for 24 hours, medication was not helping, and I was so out of it and in so much pain from this headache I was stuck in bed other than shuffling to the bathroom. This is not normal for me as I am generally healthy. I was a little better the next day but was still very dizzy and weak. I did have headaches but not as bad as that first one. Those lasted through Monday. I slept a lot and even got a COVID-19 test about five days after the vaccine to make sure I did not have COVID-19. About two weeks after that I went to my doctor, they did a neurological exam, a body exam, my abdomen was tender. We did blood work, Liver Enzymes. Checked thyroid, CBD, Liver panel. It came back that my liver enzymes were very high, about five times as high as normal as they would be. They were still elevated a month later and I am now seeing a Hepatologist next month. My doctor also concluded I should not get a Moderna vaccine again and we are holding off on a second booster due to this as well even though I did well with my first and second dose of Pfizer.

text: Admission Date: 9/18/2022 Discharge Date: 09/22/2022  DISCHARGE DIAGNOSES 1. Generalized weakness - improved 2. COVID 3. Multiple Sclerosis 4. Essential HTN 5. Depression  HOSPITAL COURSE: Patient is a 61 y.o. male who presented with generalized weakness in the setting of severe multiple sclerosis and was admitted for observation. He did not have other significant COVID signs or symptoms. He is wheelchair bound at baseline, self sufficient in transfers, but on admission was not able to complete self transfers. Neurology recommended brain and cervical spine MRI to rule out any relapse of MS. MRI brain showed Moderate volume right matter signal abnormality compatible with history of multiple sclerosis. No lesion enhancement. Therefore, generalized weakness was attributed to COVID infection. Patient was started on started solumedrol 40 mg IV q8 on 9/20 to help improve symptoms due to COVID, and given his history of multiple sclerosis.  Patient continued to improve with working with PT/OT, and it was determined that he could be discharged home safely with home health.    Patient sent home to complete 7 day course of oral prednisone 40 mg. Patient discharged with home health/PT in place. He was discharged in stable condition, back to near baseline function.
labels: Malaise, Multiple sclerosis, 19, Condition aggravated, Magnetic resonance imaging head abnormal, Asthenia, Loss of personal independence in daily activities, COVID

text: At the injection site, shortly after vaccination, the site became swollen and red with bumps. Day 2 symptoms of diarrhea, racing heart, high blood pressure (resting 121-130), loss of appetite, nausea and vomiting. Morning of day 3 she woke up with a swollen tongue, face, and throat, loss of sleep due to being scared and worried. Day 4 swelling was still prevalent. On Sep 1st, when the reaction was noticed, the patient called her family care doctor. They said that it was normal and it's nothing to worry about. Eating solid food was attempted but only apple sauce could make it past the tongue. This went on for about 5 days, the doctor's office gave an appointment via telemedicine with the assistant. No advice was given during the consultation. A follow up was done on 15 Sep with the attending doctor. This is when they explained that the pharmacy where the shot was administered would need to be told about the reactions. The Pharmacy said the patient would have to fill out the form on the website. The patient is now doing fine but during the reaction no one was trying to get her in touch with VAERS. This caused a delay in reporting and added more confusion to the situation.

text: Breakthrough COVID infection following  full 2-dose vaccination.  I tested positive for COVID 19  6 months after receiving second dose of Moderna vaccine.   Symptoms included fever lasting 8 days (99 - 101 degrees), body aches, fatique, headache, late onset dry tracheal cough, painful raised red rash on scalp and forhead with forehead edema, swollen and painful lymph nodes on head and neck, food tasted bland, single swollen/painful joint on right hand lasting 36 hours. I recovered at home and required no medical treatment.  I took over-the-counter cough suppresant, Tylenol, and Ibuprophen for symptoms.  I also took Vitamin D, Zinc, and Vitamin C during illness.

text: COVID+ 10/22/22 Vaccination status - Pfizer x4 BRIEF OVERVIEW: Admission Date: 10/22/2022 Discharge Date: 10/23/2022   DETAILS OF HOSPITAL STAY:  Clinical Narrative:  Admitted after a fall and dehydration/mild rhabdomyolysis. Myoglobinuria. Did well with hydration. Renal functions stable. Incidental note of mild cough. Covid positive. See below discussion. Preferred home based care. See discussion. Home today.   Please see the following problem-list oriented Hospital Course below:  * Rhabdomyolysis Assessment & Plan  Likely secondary to his fall and being down to the evening and early morning hours.  He is also on a statin which will be held.  Will hydrate.  Recheck CK in a.m.  CK a bit higher, as expected, but renal function normal and low enough that the Rhabdo will not be likely to impact renal function. Renal function stable. Push fluids at home. Stop Statin. The patient and his wife feel that the Statin has actually been contributing to his muscular discomfort (prior to the fall) and they will take a holiday from taking it.  Type 2 diabetes mellitus with hyperglycemia Assessment & Plan  Denies recent hypoglycemia.  Was placed on a basal bolus regimen with glipizide on hold until further trends are available.  A1C 7.2  Remained on bolus insulin back-up given the D5 solution. One time use. Improved off of the solution.  Hypothyroidism Assessment & Plan  Reports multiple recent adjustments in his thyroid.  TSH was slightly low today though his free thyroxine level is 1.1.  Recheck in 6 weeks.  Dysphagia Assessment & Plan  See above.  Resolved, per patient report. No s/s during his time on the unit.  Oropharyngeal cancer Assessment & Plan  States he finished radiation therapy and chemotherapy summer of 2021. He does have a dry mouth and throat is result.  He does have a history of dysphagia as well but states this had improved to the point were no other dietary consistency adjustments were required.  He denies dysphagia to solids and liquids at present.  It is somewhat unclear why he has been falling forward.  His neurological exam seems relatively benign but will obtain CT head in a.m.  10/23 - CT head stable. F/u with PCP/Oncology. No evidence of recurrence.  COVID-19 Assessment & Plan  Mild cough of several days duration.  Wife was enquiring about Paxlovid. This is a possibility.  Will also check a film array.  Chest x-ray clear.  Recheck chest x-ray in a.m..  MDI as he has used this in the past.  We did discuss the outpatient process for obtaining Paxlovid and will attempt to assist with this should it be needed and should the patient be discharged tomorrow.   10/23 - Discussed Paxlovid with Pharmacist. Discussed indications and dosing. Cr Cl > 65, recent symptoms onset, meets criteria.   CXR with possible mild bibasilar infiltrates. O2 needs normal. Will discuss options with patient. He is at risk of other atypical infections. Film array pending. Add Azithromycin or Doxy.  Discussed with patient and wife in detail. Functional status back to normal. States he "can do this at home". Remarkably few symptoms and CXR findings subtle. He prefers to not stay for Remdesivir and we discussed that if the Covid screen had not been positive we may not have done a CXR with his mild symptoms. He does want to consider Paxlovid and I discussed this with the pharmacist at the patient's retail pharmacy to ensure the ability to procure. I've discussed circumstances in which he should call me or return to the hospital/ED. His Oxygen needs are stable. He has no dyspnea or fever.  Dehydration Assessment & Plan  Hydrate.  Recheck renal functions in a.m.  Improved.  Essential hypertension Assessment & Plan  Will check orthostatic blood pressure and pulse.  Follow-up.  Home meds reviewed.  - remained stable  Penicillin allergy Assessment & Plan  The patient does have a cough.  Unclear if this was related to the positive COVID test or other etiology.  A full film array will be obtained.  Chest x-ray clear.  No evidence of clear pneumonia or pulmonary infiltrates present.  Penicillin allergy noted in the event that antibiotics required.  Will provide Doxycycline on discharge. Hx of H/N Cancer and prior health-care exposures.                - reviewed guidelines on drug interactions and doxycycline was not on any of the list of anti-infectives of concern.                - he has no clinically significant hepatic dysfunction or insufficiency to require dose adjustment or concern. He will have repeat LFTs off of Crestor.  INPATIENT PROCEDURES:  CT Head without acute change.

text: Chills on the night of the vaccination, followed the next day by flu-like symptoms of muscle and joint aches, flushed face, and lethargy accompanied by large red spot on left underarm.  By the morning of the 3rd day, the redness had spread to a 6" x 5" area with tenderness.  I went to the clinic and was told by the nurse that it was cellulitis and to try hot and cold packs to stimulate circulation of the blood to flush out the inflammation.  By bedtime that night the redness with swelling had become 14" long x 5" wide, covering an area from the armpit past the elbow onto the lower arm.  Finally, on the 4th day the redness began to dissipate, eventually disappearing four days later.    When given the vaccination I asked the administering nurse whether or not to expect any side effects.  He said, "Oh, no.  It's not like those flu vaccines."  This was a revaccination for me and I was later told by the Advice Nurse at the clinic that about 20% of patients have this cellulitis allergic reaction!
labels: Myalgia, Flushing, Tenderness, Arthralgia, Erythema, Cellulitis, Lethargy

text: Delta/Omicron BA.1 coinfection/ previously vaccinated with two doses of the Pfizer/ BioNTech COVID-19 vaccination almost a year prior; Delta/Omicron BA.1 coinfection/ previously vaccinated with two doses of the Pfizer/ BioNTech COVID-19 vaccination almost a year prior; This is a literature report for the following literature source(s):   A 70-year-old female patient received BNT162b2 (BNT162B2), as dose 1, single (Batch/Lot number: unknown) and as dose 2, single (Batch/Lot number: unknown) for covid-19 immunisation. The patient's relevant medical history included: "uncontrolled type II diabetes" (ongoing); "loss of taste" (unspecified if ongoing); "persistent cough" (unspecified if ongoing). The patient's concomitant medications were not reported.  The following information was reported: DRUG INEFFECTIVE (hospitalization, medically significant) with onset Jan2022, outcome "unknown", COVID-19 (hospitalization, medically significant) with onset Jan2022, outcome "recovered" (2022) and all described as "Delta/Omicron BA.1 coinfection/ previously vaccinated with two doses of the Pfizer/ BioNTech COVID-19 vaccination almost a year prior". The patient was hospitalized for drug ineffective, covid-19 (hospitalization duration: 3 day(s)). The patient underwent the following laboratory tests and procedures: Blood glucose: (Jan2022) hyperglycemic; Body temperature: (Jan2022) unknown results, notes: afebrile; SARS-CoV-2 test: (Jan2022) Delta/Omicron BA.1; Serology test: (Jan2022) unknown result. Therapeutic measures were not taken as a result of drug ineffective, covid-19.  Clinical course: An additional Delta/Omicron BA.1 coinfection in a 70-year-old female with uncontrolled type II diabetes. This case was notable as it occurred overlapped temporally with the coinfection at the beginning of January 2022 when both the Delta and Omicron BA.1 VOCs were present in the community in relative abundance. Upon presentation the patient was afebrile but complained of a loss of taste and persistent cough. The patient was previously vaccinated with two doses of the Pfizer/ BioNTech COVID-19 vaccination almost a year prior, but her serological status was unknown. At the time of presentation, the patient was profoundly hyperglycemic which can impact immune function. Type II diabetes is a risk factor for more severe COVID-19. Thus, while not having underlying malignancy or managed with immunosuppressive drugs as others in this case series, this patient's immune status was likely dysregulated due to her comorbidity which can render her more susceptible to infection. This patient was managed without COVID-19 specific therapy and discharged 3 days later. As before, no mutational signatures consistent with SARS-CoV-2 recombination were identified in this patient's respiratory specimens.  The lot number for BNT162b2 was not provided and will be requested during follow up.; Sender's Comments: The vaccine efficacy varies from one patient to another and can be affected by different factors; however, a contributory role of the suspect vaccine BNT162B2 to its Lack of efficacy cannot be ruled out.  The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to regulatory authorities, Ethics Committees, and Investigators, as appropriate.,Linked Report(s) : US-PFIZER INC-202201301194 Same article/ drug/event and different patient;

text: Dizziness; unable to read labels; Inability to use any limbs including neck; could not talk; weakness; blood pressure low; blood sugar low; Sudden urge to urinate; Vision blurriness; Fatigue; This spontaneous case was reported by a consumer and describes the occurrence of DIZZINESS (Dizziness), VISUAL IMPAIRMENT (unable to read labels), MOVEMENT DISORDER (Inability to use any limbs including neck), SPEECH DISORDER (could not talk) and ASTHENIA (weakness) in a 55-year-old female patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (batch nos. 045A20A and 042?21A) for COVID-19 vaccination. The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below.     The patient's past medical history included Bipolar affective disorder. Concurrent medical conditions included Drug allergy (Bactrim, baclofen) and Penicillin allergy. Concomitant products included CLONAZEPAM (KLONOPIN) for Anxiety, TRAZODONE HYDROCHLORIDE (TRAZODONE) for Depression, LAMOTRIGINE (LAMICTAL) for Mood change, QUETIAPINE FUMARATE (SEROQUEL) for Psychosis, LISDEXAMFETAMINE MESILATE (VYVANSE) and MIRTAZAPINE for an unknown indication.   On 24-Mar-2021 at 12:30 PM, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 20-Apr-2021, received second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (unknown route) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. On 23-Mar-2021, the patient experienced DIZZINESS (Dizziness), VISUAL IMPAIRMENT (unable to read labels), MOVEMENT DISORDER (Inability to use any limbs including neck), SPEECH DISORDER (could not talk), ASTHENIA (weakness), HYPOTENSION (blood pressure low), BLOOD GLUCOSE DECREASED (blood sugar low), MICTURITION URGENCY (Sudden urge to urinate), VISION BLURRED (Vision blurriness) and FATIGUE (Fatigue). The patient was treated with DIPHENHYDRAMINE HYDROCHLORIDE (BENADRYL [DIPHENHYDRAMINE HYDROCHLORIDE]) at an unspecified dose and frequency. text: Eczema; Skin rash on scalp/ ankles/ footA/ wrist/ elbows and buttocks; Allergy; Fatigue; This spontaneous case was reported by a consumer and describes the occurrence of ECZEMA (Eczema), RASH (Skin rash on scalp/ ankles/ footA/ wrist/ elbows and buttocks), HYPERSENSITIVITY (Allergy) and FATIGUE (Fatigue) in a 64-year-old female patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) for COVID-19 vaccination. Co-suspect product included non-company product ADALIMUMAB (HUMIRA) for Panuveitis. No Medical History information was reported. On 04-Mar-2021, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 01-Apr-2021, received second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. On an unknown date, the patient started ADALIMUMAB (HUMIRA) (Subcutaneous) at an unspecified dose. In April 2021, the patient experienced FATIGUE (Fatigue). On an unknown date, the patient experienced ECZEMA (Eczema), RASH (Skin rash on scalp/ ankles/ footA/ wrist/ elbows and buttocks) and HYPERSENSITIVITY (Allergy). At the time of the report, ECZEMA (Eczema), RASH (Skin rash on scalp/ ankles/ foot/ wrist/ elbows and buttocks) and HYPERSENSITIVITY (Allergy) had not resolved and FATIGUE (Fatigue) outcome was unknown.            Concomitant medication was not reported.  Treatment medication was not reported.  The patient had non-serious fatigue, eczema, skin rashes on scalp, ankles, foot/ wrist/ elbows and buttocks and allergies with humira.  This case was identified as part of a retrospective clean-up activity where certain emails received in the Moderna mailbox were missed to be booked-in.
labels: Hypersensitivity, Eczema, Fatigue, Rash

text: Extreme chills with four degrees of fever with low blood pressure. My heart was beating very fast...much faster than normal and my heart and lungs felt like they were in an oven cooking. Then I was feeling achy and my other insides felt warm and ackey. The tops of both of my arms became red like I had been in the sun which lasted for days. I was also short of breath. I told my son the next day that if he left, when he came back, I might be dead. I stayed in bed. My oxygen level we t down a bit. I finally took some aspirin and some Tylenol. Five days later I felt better but I feel like I will not get vaccines any longer after that and I may have had some sort of heart inflamation. I am sorry that I did the moderna vaccine. I will be telling my doctors a out this. We will be seeing if my body is damaged. The scariest part was the fast heart beat and it feeling hurtful and hot in my chest. You knew something was happening. I had also felt my heart squeezing on the tenth and eleventh day on the first shot.

text: Flu like symptoms; Weakness; Headache; Tiredness; just sleeping /. She slept it off for a couple of days./felt very sleepy; she could feel her heart racing; had a heavy feeling on her head; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer (patient) or other non hcp.  A 78-year-old female patient received first dose of bnt162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 mRNA VACCINE, Formulation: Solution for injection, Lot number and Expiration date were unknown), via an unspecified route of administration on 26Jan2021 10:00 (at the age of 78-years-old) as 1ST DOSE, SINGLE for covid-19 immunisation.  Medical history included asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease from an unspecified date, diagnosed many years ago. Broken collarbone and Broken wrist on 28Dec2020. It was reported that she had three broken bones in her wrist, she can't lay in bed anyway, so she sleeps on the sofa, getting constipated on an unspecified date, The patient was allergic to Benadryl. It was also reported that she doesn't sleep too well, due to the sitting up in the chair business. concomitant medications were not reported. On 26Jan2021, 2-3 hours after, she felt very sleepy, had a heavy feeling on her head that was almost flu-ish but had no fever nor chills, and she felt that her heart was racing Influenza like illness, weakness, headache, and tiredness. She slept it off for a couple of days. She was enquired if she can still take the 2nd dose of the vaccine given these side effects. It was reported that she had her first dose of the shot on the 26th of Jan and thinks she had a reaction, though it was not enough to go to her doctor or anything, she was too weak. She said she didn't have chills, was not nauseous, had no fever, she feels like she had the flu, and. She said that she gets up and eats then goes back to sleep or does whatever else she had to do. she can't lay in bed anyway so she sleeps on the sofa. she did get up the next day and all the time had a headache. She says she doesn't take the flu shot because her older brother had a terrible reaction to that, none of her siblings take that shot, but she knows what it feels like to have a bad cold with your head heavy, that kind of feeling, she imagines that is what the flu feels like. The patient received treatment with Tylenol for headache. The patient underwent lab tests and procedures which included blood pressure (blood pressure measurement): 110/70 mmHg on an unspecified date, blood test: unknown on an unspecified date, Pulse (heart rate): pulse was ok on an unspecified date. Caller said that she was so surprised when she went to her doctor's appointment that her heart was racing, and she thought her blood pressure would be sky high, but the bottom number was 70 something, which is low for her, and the top number was 110, so it was perfect, which she doesn't usually have. She said that her pulse was ok and everything else was ok, and she had blood work taken that day but they didn't get those results back yet, so she doesn't know what they are. text: GNA approached this nurse and reported resident had bloody nose. Upon entering room, resident noted sitting in W/C holding bloody kleenex to nose. This nurse spoke with resident and she asked me to pinch her nose for her. While pinching nose, resident coughed up bloody clots and spit them into kleenex. This continued for several minutes as resident blew her nose and spit up clots. Cold pack held to bridge of nose slowed the nose bleed however resident continued to cough up bloody clots.  Resident's body stiffened, her head went back and jerked for a few seconds as this nurse held her head upright. Resident did not appear to be breathing, she was placed into bed and staff were unable to obtain BP or HR or respirations, eyes fixed and dilated. Paramedic arrived and called TOD @ 1545.

text: HOSPITAL COURSE: The patient is a 61-year-old female with a history of intellectual disability and developmental delay, uncontrolled diabetes not on any medications with A1c 11.5, presenting to the hospital for weakness.   Hospital course:   In the emergency room the patient was found to be tachycardic and tachypneic with elevated WBC, dimer, sodium to 159, glucose to 742 with elevated creatinine and lactate.  Suspected HHS, started on insulin and dextrose.  Patient was found to be COVID-positive 1/11/2022.  Right middle lobe infiltrate seen on imaging, CT scan of the chest, started on antibiotics for suspected bacterial pneumonia.  Patient was not hypoxic.   Patient was initially admitted to the ICU on insulin drip, blood sugars quickly improved.  Patient did not have good oral intake throughout the early portion of her hospitalization and was resistant to taking oral intake despite return to her baseline level mental status.  Speech pathology consulted.  Electrolytes and renal function slowly returned back to normal on D5W drip.  Patient had elevated dimer but CT scan of the chest and lower extremity Doppler ultrasounds were negative for VTE.  Continued on standard dose DVT prophylaxis with enoxaparin.   By 1/17 she had continued stability and remained at her baseline mental status. She continued to deny food and PO intake. It is thought that her poor PO intake was behavioral with maybe some contribution from lack of taste 2/2 COVID.  SLP was unable to work w/ patient due to refusal of eating/drinking or participating with their assessment.  She also does not have cognitive capacity to participate in exam and explain why she is refusing to eat. This was discussed with her sisteer who is primary caregiver. She expressed pt likes specific foods and can refuse things if she doesn't want it.  Again thought her PO intake was behavioral. Due to this, the best plan for improving her PO intake was determined to be getting back home to a familiar setting with her sister and foods she likes.  Discussed this with her sister who was in agreement and excited to have her sister come home. Plans were for DC on 1/19 evening, however family called later in the evening and reported they could not provide support / cares until the morning as they were making arrangements. Pt DC on 1/20/22   For more detail, please see admission H&P.  Hospital course dictated by problem:     Suspected HHS Hypernatremia Hyperkalemia, hypokalemia Dehydration Acute Kidney Injury/Acute Renal Failure As above. Lytes normalized and AKI resolved.     Chronic type 2 diabetes with acute hyperglycemia, A1c 11.5 Poor oral intake As above, poor intake thought to be behavioral and best mgmt plan is to return home to familiar environment and foods she enjoys.  PTA on metformin 1000mg BID. Per family sugars are not as controlled as they would like but they have found a good balance with this as the patient does not tolerate insulin very well (injection). Per family pt has enough metformin at home and no refills needed.     COVID-19 without COVID-pneumonia Elevated dimer due to the above Suspected bacterial community-acquired pneumonia Suspect severe sepsis due to the above Leukocytosis -Finished 5-day course of ceftriaxone azithromycin -CTPA and lower extremity Doppler ultrasounds negative for VTE     Chronic developmental delay, intellectual disability Low T3 level -Outpatient follow-up for thyroid   DISCHARGE DIAGNOSES:  Principal Problem:   Hyperosmolar hyperglycemic state (HHS) (HCC) Active Problems:   Type 2 diabetes mellitus without complication, without long-term current use of insulin (HCC)   Developmental delay   COVID-19   Pneumonia, suspected bacterial

LPRD (laryngopharyngeal reflux disease) 11/29/2017 Unknown   Discharge Disposition:  home or self care  DETAILS OF HOSPITAL STAY: PRESENTING PROBLEM: Pulmonary infiltrates [R91.8] Hemoptysis [R04.2] Immunosuppressed status  [D84.9] Fever, unspecified fever cause [R50.9] COVID-19 virus infection [U07.1]   HOSPITAL COURSE:  Patient is a vaccinated (J&J 4/10/21, no booster) and immune suppressed 51 yo woman who was admitted to Hospital with fever and shortness of breath. She was sent to the hospital from her Rheumatologist's office, Dr., during a visit for a second dose of rituximab; he and staff advised she present to the emergency department after report of ongoing fever at which point she was admitted.   She carries dx of complex tracheal stenosis (hx dilation w/ mitomycin and Kenalog) and microscopic polyangiitis, ANCA-associated vasculitis, for which she has been working with Rheumatology, Dr., and taking Imuran, recent steroid, and recent first dose of Rituximab. She arrived taking oral estrogen for menopausal symptoms.   Fever persisted for most of her stay, typically in the early morning hours around 4-6 AM with her last recorded fever at 12/26/21 AM, the day prior to discharge.  Her shortness of breath was mild, O2 saturations remained at 90 and above, and supplemental oxygen was never used but her CXR w/ mild pulmonary infiltrates were noted a negative nasal swab source for Covid PCR, but was positive on BAL from bronchoscopy 12/23/21. No diffuse alveolar hemorrhage (DAH) was confirmed by bronch so infiltrates were though possibly due to Covid pneumonia. She was given prednisone 20 mg daily, an increase from recent start of 15 mg daily for her vasculitis.   Symptom start of most current fever and sense of illness was 12/19/21 based on her calendar, and was distinct from prior once monthly fevers since summer 2021.  Pulmonology recommended monoclonal antibody which was arranged 12/25/21. ID weighed in and did not express confidence infection was the reason for fevers over past 6 mos, that it is possible recent sx are from Covid infection. It was recommended: o she have COVID-19 antibody levels collected in approximately 3 months to determine if she developed nuclear capsid antibodies following this infection. o She should receive at least 1 booster vaccine, preferably mRNA vaccine either Pfizer or Moderna.  She will need to wait at least 90 days after her monoclonal antibody infusion before booster vaccine can be given. o If she does not develop antibodies following her current infection, she may be a candidate for prophylactic monoclonal antibody administration.  Her immunologist can contact the Infectious Disease office or the monoclonal antibody infusion clinic at that time to determine if there are any clinical trials that would be beneficial for this patient. These recommendations were provided in writing in her DC material for her reference. Dr., her Rheumatologist, then weighed in and recommended continued HOLD on Imuran at discharge and wanted her to be, 1) 2-3 weeks out from antibiotic treatment for possible bacterial pneumonia, and 2) feeling well.   CRP was high on admission and it was not clear if this was a useful measure in the setting of chronic inflammation.   Rocephin and azithro empiric for CAP to be completed orally if discharged  CAP tx was completed in hospital but her probability of bacterial pneumonia was in question.  Leukopenia resolved during her stay, with hold on Imuran, despite Covid infection, etc. Bactrim PJP ppx, Hydroxychloroquine, Valtrex, Lyrica and PPI continued   Hot flashes from acute-onset menopause due to HOLD on oral estrogen in setting of Covid infection (indication to avoid adding to any hypercoagulable state from Covid infection).  She was able to tell the difference between hot flashes and illness, especially fever given she got cold with fever, not hot.   Dysuria had been intermittent per her report. UA 12/22/21 contained calcium oxalate crystals, and neither this nor a second collection 12/23/21 contained support for infection. Had there been infection, abx for CAP would likely have offered coverage.   She discharged home 12/27/21 feeling well compared to prior (but we appreciate she had not suffered fever the morning of discharge) with plan to follow up with her Rheumatologist. A leukemia / lymphoma w/u was pending at discharge and will require follow-up Prednisone was to resume at dose prior to admission, 15 mg daily. text: I had very severe cf starting in 1996.  It remained severe for approximately 5 years after which it was semi acute for another 5 years.    After that i would have periodic relapses several times a year for varying lengths of time.  For the last 10 years irt has been much better with occasional symptoms.  However i received my second dose of the Moderna vaccine on february 23, 2021 and had a strong flu like response.  I am now experiencing a mild to moderate relapse of my cf.   brain fog, difficulty tracking with my vision, chills, etc.  when i had severe cf i had this symptom where my scalp would feellike it was in a spasm.  That has returned.  I have dealt with tcf long enough to know when it occurs and this is definitely a response to the covid vaccine.
labels: Feeling abnormal, Cystic fibrosis, Influenza like illness, Chills, Visual impairment, Sensory disturbance

text: I received my second Moderna booster on 7/14/2022. On 8/20/2022, I woke up at 6 AM congested and achy all over. I also had nausea and vomiting, plus a cough. On 8/21/2022, I went to an urgent care clinic to get tested for COVID-19. I was tested for both COVID-19 and the flu, and the results on both were negative. I was given TESSALON for my cough and told to go home and isolate, as I had yet to get the results of the COVID-19 test. Even though I got a negative test result, I decided to self-isolate for the rest of the month. I felt better around 9/1/2022 and resumed my regular routine. On the morning of 9/8/2022, I woke up with head congestion, cough, and body aches. I took a home test and got a positive result. I had a telehealth visit with my PA that day, and I was prescribed PAXLOVID. I picked it up on 9/9/2022 and began taking it that day. I also began self-isolating again. I stayed at home until about 9/27/2022 and I then resumed my normal activities.
labels: Cough, Loss of personal independence in daily activities, 19, COVID, 2 test positive, Nausea, Influenza virus test negative, Respiratory tract congestion, CoV, Vomiting, Pain, SARS, Head discomfort

text: I stay at my parents the night before work because their home is located much closer to work--my fiance and I live much farther away.   I received the vaccination around 10AM Sunday morning.  Sunday night I went to bed around 8:30PM and experienced severe chills throughout the night.  I awoke around 12AM and got up to get a drink.  I got a drink of water and checked my temperature, temp was 100.7.  I felt yucky but not horrible.  I walked back to my parents' room to tell them I would be staying home from work.  As I got to their room and began to speak, I began to feel nauseous and weak and suddenly collapsed.  My dad leaped up and helped me stand up so I could get to the restroom.  I walked a few steps and then collapsed again and lost complete consciousness--I do not recall collapsing again or what happened shortly after.  Per my dad, I was unresponsive, and he drug my limp body from his bedroom to the bathroom.  My mom called 911.  After several minutes, I regained consciousness and was leaning against my dad in the bathroom.  I felt my fever break and was sweating profusely.  EMS arrived at my home and checked vitals--everything was stable.  I was A&O x3 and was able to drink water.   I declined being transported to the hospital.  I felt the loss of consciousness was likely due to dehydration or fever (although my fever really wasn't that high).
labels: Sleep disorder, Body temperature increased, Loss of consciousness, Asthenia, Impaired work ability, Nausea, Hyperhidrosis, Malaise, Unresponsive to stimuli, Chills

text: I was tired and feeling run down. I thought maybe I just wasn't sleeping well. The night of July 6th, I started to feel achy, like if I was coming down with something. I was congested and incredibly fatigued. I was trying to work but I had to sleep after every other. To this day I can only work very few hours before I have to lay down and nap. I work a desk job so I am not doing labor. The top part of my head feels like its to tight. I currently am experiencing still heavy fatigue and a headache even though I just recently tested negative again.

text: Immediately broke out in a sweat and was very hot.  Didn't think much about it.  The staff noticed I was in some distress and kept asking if I was okay to which I replied I thought I'd be fine once I got some fresh air.  Left the facility to drive home and didn't feel right, Within 30 minutes, developed chest pains, rash and labored breathing.  I recognize the symptoms as the same symptoms I get when I've had morphine, which I now must list as an allergy.  This lasted 4 hours, then got better.  The next day around 1:00, I became ill again with flu-like symptoms and had to leave work.  Headache and body aches mostly.  I was ill with these symptoms for a 24 hour period.  Hopefully all symptoms have passed, except my arm which is red, swollen, itchy and feverish.

text: Initial report received on 18 June 2012 from the Investigator participating in the post-marketing observational study under the reference number M5A16. A case of pertussis disease in a six-month-old female subject was identified by the investigator based on review of data from the Electronic Disease Surveillance (EDSS) electronic database. The subject had received 3 doses of PENTACEL; lot number C3952AA received on 09 December 2011, lot number C4130AA received on 01 February 2012 and lot number C4081AA received on 24 April 2012 (routes and sites of administration not reported). The subject developed a cough on 03 May 2012, approximately 9 days after the last dose and a paroxysmal cough on an unspecified date with a whoop. The subject also experienced posttussive vomiting. Laboratory testing included negative PCR on 17 May 2012. Chest x-ray findings were negative for pneumonia. Corrective treatments consisted of azithromycin starting on 17 May 2012 for 5 days. The subject was not hospitalized. At the time of final contact on 24 May 2012, the subject's cough was still persisting. The duration of the cough was reported at that time as 21 days. According to the investigator, this case was epidemiologically linked to a laboratory confirmed case. Investigator causality assessment is not required as per protocol. Documents held by sender: None.

text: It started with a rash with hives and whelps on my torso and arms. Then it turned into Mass Cell Activation Syndrome. I contacted my doctor on January 13th and then I begin having symptoms in other portions of my body like my gastrointestinal. I had heartburn, tingling in mouth and tongue. Spasms in extremities. I had weakness in my legs along with numbness in the extremities. I experienced lightheadedness, dizziness and fatigue. I had esophageal spasm. I am being treated with antihistamines and supplements. Blood work was completed and I was referred to an immunologist and a rheumatologist. I am still experiencing all of the same symptoms, It's like a histamine reaction that's affecting the majority of the systems in my body.

text: Low grade fever (100.7), chills, body aches, headache, fatigue, mild nausea, hypersensitivity to sound, and a deep sense of doom/sadness/despair, which could have been severe fatigue.  I took Tylenol which didn't help. I called CVS and spoke to the pharmacist who said to also take an NSAID, which I did several times over a few days.  These clinical signs mostly resolved w/in 24 hours, except the fatigue and headache.  I was exhausted and slept a lot during the following week.   I also began to have chest flutters, flashes of dizziness and flashes of doom/despair in the middle of concentrating on something completely different, like at work.  I listened to my heart with a stethoscope after the flutter event was over and there was no arrhythmia at that time of auscultation and my HR was 74-80.   Each of these happened a few times the next week. Now those are mostly gone.   I continue to be tired and fatigue easily and need to take 1-2 hr naps in the middle of the day or after work, when I can.    Yesterday at work (4/13/21) I had extra sensitivity reaction to a repeated high pitched noise which, though didn't seem like would cause a lasting issue, then did cause me to be very fatigued and agitated afterward.  I also did then have an earache which hasn't resolved.  I am not sure if related to my original sound sensitivity.    A person I work with, who previously had COVID and got her 1st Pfizer shot last Saturday, also described she was having chest flutters, tachycardia, and feelings of doom several times over the last few days, which validated my own experience of signs after my vaccination.
labels: Nausea, Headache, Fatigue, Dizziness, Pyrexia, Chills, Anxiety, Ear pain, Pain, Hyperacusis

text: Menses delayed by 3 months, then 2 months, then back to regular schedule.  Estrogen and FSH levels are testing at post-menopausal levels even though I am not experiencing any menopausal symptoms,  I did FSH and Estrogen labs 3x during the menses pause and after they resumed to regular schedule.  All three lab results show levels consistent with post-menopause.   My ob-gyn is confused.  Also 4 hours after the first dose of my vaccine, I experienced covid-like symptoms, shortness of breath, heart palpitations, and high BP.  I went to Urgent Care the next morning and was referred to ER where they ran blood tests to ensure I was not having a heart attack, tests came clean and after 4 hours of IV, my BP came down and they released me.  I felt woozy and weak for the next 4 days, the doctor said they have seen this reaction before and said I should expect to feel the same way after the 2nd dose but for a two week time span.  She told me to monitor my oxygen and BP levels and come back if they dipped. It was okay, I was just very fatigued and out of breath a lot for the next few days.   It was scary.   I finally got my 2nd dose 8 months later and so far no adverse symptoms.   This time I made to sure to sleep well consistently before the shot.  For the first dose I was averaging less than 4 hours of sleep per day, I think sleep may be related to reaction for me.

text: Moderna shot administered on 2/12/21 10 minutes after shot feeling of warmth, sweating, racing heart and feeling of uneasiness l ike something was wrong. Weird sensation i n throat area. -went to nurses and EMT at vaccination site and described feeling that something was wrong EMT checked pulse, blood pressure, oxygen l evels: heart rate was elevated and blood pressure was 150/?. EMT advised taking deep breaths and getting rechecked i n 10 minutes. Heart rate and blood pressure went down to 130/?. EMT wanted to recheck i n 15 minutes to make sure heart rate stayed down. When rechecked i t was back to 150/?. EMT advised getting checked out at urgent care and advised that I not drive myself. Went to urgent care right after l eaving the vaccination site. When nurse checked blood pressure i t was 178/? And heart rate was 135 bpm. Nurse mentioned some swelling around injection site that I should keep an eye on. Temperature was 99.7 at urgent care. 10 minutes later when when doctor rechecked i t was down to 130/? And pulse was down to normal range. Doctor advised that i t could be an allergic reaction and to make sure I had benadryl on hand i n case reaction worsened. Over night after vaccineI had chills and then a headache i n the morning upon waking. Slight temperature no higher than 100 that morning. 2/13/21 the next day at around 12:30 pm began feeling l ike I did i mmediately after the vaccine but symptoms were more i ntense. Feeling of warmth and tingling sensation throat/face. Answering service for doctor?s office advised taking benadryl and i f still not feeling symptoms resolve or i f worsening to go to ER. After taking 2 benadryl 50 mg. Symptoms were not resolving. Mentioned not feeling right to my husband and he said I had a big red welt under my chin toward throat area. Symptoms were not i mproving and felt tightness i n throat and chest area. Voice was becoming hoarse so went to ER. Nurse took vitals and asked i f I forgot to take blood pressure meds as pulse and blood pressure were both high 176/? Heart rate 140. I replied that I had never had high blood pressure before. They monitored blood pressure, pulse, oxygen l evels for several hours. As benadryl wore off redness developed across entire back area and red welt appeared on front abdomen. Blood pressure and pulse were elevated for about 2 hours going up and down until finally staying i n normal range. ER doctor prescribed high dose of prednisone for allergic reaction. Symptoms resolved and was discharged from ER. ER did EKG and CBC W/Auto differential, comprehensive metabolic blood panel, troponin, and TSH with reflex. Results were normal TSH was 3.07 uIU/mL. Wanted to check thyroid l evel as I take l evothyroxine due to hypothyroidism 100 mg daily. 2 days l ater as steroids wore off began feeling burning sensations on skin i n different areas stomach, back, face and took benadryl for 3 days until symptoms resolved. Took blood pressure at home with automatic blood pressure cuff and i t remained elevated off and on for several days 150/? Until Wednesday that week went i t stayed under 130 consistently. Also wear a watch and resting heart rate was reading up to 135 bpm at night during sleep until Tuesday of that same week. 2 weeks after vaccine feelings of swollen l ymph nodes under both armpits when raising arms or putting on clothing. Shot was given i n l eft arm. Allergy History To Medications: Ciprofloxacin- swelling and tingling i n face Sulfa- Hives Cefixime Tingly i n l ips and tongue

text: More than 30 days after receiving the Janssen vaccine, I tested positive for COVID-19.  Symptoms began as runny nose, sneezing, and sinus pressure/burning on April 6, 2021.  Tested for COVID-19 on April 11, 2021 (nasal swab, PCR test) after a family member tested positive.  Symptoms worsened on April 12, 2021, including shortness of breath, chest pain, complete loss of taste and smell.  Sought treatment for breathing difficulty at ER on April 13, 2021 (Vidant Medical Center and was instructed to rest at home.  Sought treatment for breathing difficulty at PCP on April 14, 2021 ( Medical Center) and prescribed Prednisone.  Symptoms worsened on April 15, 2021, including shortness of breath, chest pain, numbness in face/arms/legs, dizziness, loss of balance, memory and speaking difficulty, near fainting.  Sought treatment at ER on April 15, 2021 (Vidant Medical Center, Greenville, NC).  Held for three days, treated with Remdesivir (3 doses) and supplemental oxygen.  Discharged from hospital on April 18, 2021.  Symptoms did not improve following discharge.  Sought treatment for ongoing symptoms at ER on April 21, 2021, instructed to rest at home.  Symptoms continued to worsen on April 24, 2021, including shortness of breath, chest pain, numbness in face/arms/legs, dizziness, loss of balance, memory and speaking difficulty, near fainting, and slurred/incoherent speech.  Sought treatment at ER on April 15, 2021, admitted to hospital on April 25, 2021 diagnosed with probable TIA.  Treated with Optiflow high-flow oxygen therapy, nebulizer, and steroids.  Received a variety of tests and scans of head, neck, spine, chest, heart; none showed signs of any serious cardiac, vascular, or neurological problems.  Transferred to in-patient rehabilitation on May 1, 2021 for physical and occupational therapy.  Discharged from in-patient rehabilitation on May 6, 2021.  Prescribed out-patient physical and occupational therapy to resolve remaining dizziness, balance, and endurance deficits.

text: My daughter came down with a fever for 5 days starting on Feb 19 which was 6 days after her MMR and Varicella vaccines.  According to multiple sources online her reaction was consistent to a reaction to the Measles portion of the vaccine.  She did have a minor rash. She continued with fever and not wanting to eat anything and her illness and fever progressed from there to a possible diagnosis of Mono about a week later which was based on a monospot test which according to the CDC is not very reliable in children and her Epstein Barr results were not returned or shipped to facility because of inclement weather (that's where they send bloodwork for Epstein Barr.) She got worse after the "diagnosis". She developed a terrible crust over her eyes that kept coming throughout the day for over about a week and her nose was terribly full of snot.  She was not eating still and I was having to give her Ensure everyday along with her fluids for 7 weeks to keep her "fed."  Her white count at the time of the Mono diagnosis was 23,000.  She was still not eating on her own much by the first week in April (only a bite here and there) I was continuing to talk with nurse periodically about her condition on the phone and I was continuing to keep her hydrated and give her Ensure at home. On April 9th she came down with 104 fever and we tried to treat her at home for a couple of days but there was no change so on April 11 we took her to the ER and I spent 5 hours there with her as they ran tests for everything imaginable.  Her white count was still very high (22,000) and according to the ER doc nothing was showing us the cause of the fever but he decided to treat her symptom (fever) as a bacterial infection. Later on her doctor told me that the xray report showed a tiny sign of something that could have been early Pneumonia.  I have obtained copies of most of her records related to this situation.  Nothing ever cultured out bacterially speaking but the antibiotic that she was given has seemed to help and so far as of April 20th she has been better.  This has been a Very difficult time for our family as we have tried to figure out what could be wrong with our child.

text: Narrative: 8/21/2022 - Pt presented to ED with Bilateral lower extremities swollen. Left appears blue and pale - pulse present. Right lower extremities red / swollen / hot. Complains of SOB at rest, loose stools, cough, decreased appetite, and swelling all over especially bilateral legs x 1 week, left leg appears pale and blue / right leg appears red / warm / swollen. Covid positive at home according to patient. Patient complains of all over body aches. Patient states he has nose CA - Nose appears blue in color. Patient placed on cotninous bp pressure / pulse ox / cardiac monitoring. Respirations remain tachypneic ~28-30 with sats 94% on 4 l/nc. Pt to be admitted to SDU. Primary Diagnosis: Severe sepsis. community acquired pneumonia. Covid 19. UTI. right lower extremity cellulitis, respiratory alkalosis. demand ischemia troponemia. acute renal insufficiency. Patient is a 57 yo gentleman with RA on etanercept and prednisone, admitted the SDU on 8/21/22 with sepsis & acute hypoxic respiratory failure due to COVID, RLE cellulitis and UTI, and started on empiric cefepime and vancomycin. On 8/22/22, patient developed new onset aflutter with RVR, hypotension, worsening hypoxic respiratory failure requiring HFNC. The patient was transferred to MICU, he was started on an amiodarone gtt. Chest CTA showed evidence of bilateral PE/septic emboli and started on lovenox. The patient has persistent MRSA bacteremia, no evidence of vegetations on TTE. Pt transferred to the SDU this morning. PT treated with decadron and remdesivir.

text: Patient recieved HAV#2 on 2/3/09, went home and had a 3hr nap, mom woke patient and noticed coughing and wheezing, which continued through the night. In office Dr noted labored respirations w/few retractions and heard wheezing on right, albuterol administered via nebulizer and was clear to auscultate except for occasional crackle. Dr. then sent patient to obtain chest Xray to rule out foreign body ingestion. Patient returned from Xray w/grunting respirations and wheezes throughout, after 2nd treatment given patient was clear to auscultate. Dr then admitted patient to pediatrics to administer fluids, solumedrol, frequent neb treatments and possible O2 therapy. Patient was discharged the following day.  2/18/09 Received hospital medical records which consisted only of CXR & lab.  Medical records states only records available. text: Patient with J+J COVID vaccination on 04/01/21 who admitted to hospital with sickle cell crisis and positive COVID test, fevers, cough.  Provider d/c note below:  "Brief Summary of Hospital Stay: Patient presented to the ED on 1/2/2022 due to sickle cell pain crisis. He was started on pain medications and IVF with improvement in his symptoms. His stay was complicated by the development of fevers, he was tested for COVID and was positive. He had a cough but was otherwise asymptomatic, without shortness of breath or hypoxia. Given his risk factors for progression the patient was offered regeneron after explanation of risks and benefits and consented. He was also started on antibiotics for possible CAP. text: Prior to vaccination, the patient stated that she was nervous, but seemed relieved and okay directly following the vaccination.  Following vaccination, patient became restless during the 15 minute post-vaccination window about 2-5 minutes after receiving the vaccine.  She initially presented with uncontrollable shaking/bouncing legs, palpitation, sweating, and shortness of breath (though this was very brief.   Patient remained coherent and oriented to time/person/place.   The shaking and palpitations subsided after a couple minutes and resumed towards the end of the 15 minute waiting period, accompanied by nausea.  25 minutes post-vaccination she appeared to have stabilized, and we assisted the patient to her room nearby at her request to allow her to lie down while being monitored.  After returning to her room, she very quickly ran to her sink due to her nausea, then after a minute of attempting to vomit, she collapsed and appeared to have briefly lost consciousness.  EMS was called and the patient was rolled onto her side to prevent choking in the event of emesis.  Patient remained responsive, but was weak and clammy with a weak pulse and breathing.  After the firefighters came, a search of the apartment found the previously listed medications.  Additionally, the patient experienced a seizure-like episode lasting 15 seconds in duration.  Once the EMT came, they assessed her and monitored her in the ambulance; they reported that her condition appeared stable, her vitals were strong, and transported her to Hospital for observation/testing.
labels: Nausea, Seizure like phenomena, Dyspnoea, Asthenia, Loss of consciousness, Pulse abnormal, Cold sweat, Palpitations, Vomiting, Hyperhidrosis, Restlessness

text: She got her vaccine, and felt fine.  She came home and did what she had to do and when she went to bed she felt fine. She finally managed to get to her phone again, she was not able to get up, and she called 9-1-1 and they came out and got her in the chair, but did not take her to the hospital. text: Started getting a headache first and then about 15 minutes in, they started having me sitting on the side as a higher risk - I have had reactions to vaccines in the past. I noticed my throat itching really bad. I wasn't having trouble breathing but itching was getting really bad and there was redness on my neck and heat and then I got cold sweats. Someone came and checked my vitals and they gave me Benadryl. It helped with itching but it did not help with the cold sweats or anything like that. They advised me to go home and rest and get something to eat. I got a fever after that - it was about 102. I felt kind of tired and lethargic. I felt a little bit dizzy. Around 5 pm, I woke up and had chest pain really bad on my left upper chest. I tried to sleep through the night but work up a lot. The next day, I tried to sleep and around 09:00 pm the pain got really bad and around midnight, I tried to find someone to watch my daughter so I could go to ER but couldn't find anyone. The next day, I made an appt I went to my doctor and they did an EKG to check heart function. They did a physical exam - they said it was major inflammation in my body that was causing the pain and they put me on Prednisone (40 mg a day) for the next 5 days and then asked me to come back. Later that night, strange dull achy pains, under my last bottom rib, on the left side on middle of my abdomen, I didn't call the dr's office - that lasted through the night but in the morning that pain was gone but the chest pain I still have. I have had a headache since that day - it's off and on but it is pretty severe when it comes on. I have taken a couple of Benadryl since then due to asthmatic symptoms with allergy type stuff.

text: The patient came in for her first dose of vaccine. I verbally asked if she had any health conditions, allergies, andy reactions to previous vaccines. The mother answered for her and declined all. Once the patient filled out the paperwork and received the vaccine she stated she felt light headed. I noticed quickly she was about to faint. We put a chair under her and sat her down. She became unresponsive, but was breathing fine. She began to sweat and her pulse decreased. I asked for someone to call 911 and find her mom. I attempted to check her blood pressure but was unable because of her positioning. She was breathing fine and was answering short sentences but was speaking slow. Right after we called the ambulance she asked what happened and said she was feeling better. Shortly after the ambulance arrived and checked her out. Her mother declined transport to the hospital.
labels: Syncope, Unresponsive to stimuli, Hyperhidrosis

text: The patient developed low grade fevers 24 hours after his flu vaccine  and pfizer booster. Approx 48 hours after the vaccines, his fevers started spiking to tmax 103.7. He was treated at home until 12/26 with alternating ibuprofen and tylenol until 12/26 when, upon discussion with his primary care doc, me, he went to the ER. In ER noted to be hypotensive, tachycardic, and w fever. Also developed vomiting. Given fluids and ceftriaxone. Noted to have elevated troponin, crp, ldh. Normal chest xray. EKG with mild t wave abnormalities which resolved on second EKG. Normal bedside echo. Stabilized, sent to ICU for monitoring. Labs generally improved. Formal Echo normal. On 12/27 developed GI bleed w melanotic stool. sent for EGD and colonoscopy which showed possible mallory weiss tear/gastritis. Placed on protonix and received blood transfusion for drop of hemoglobin from 13 to 8. Advanced diet slowly.  Meanwhile ebv serology came back igm positive, heterophile neg. CMV igm also positive. NO EBV DNA found.  Patient stablized well with down trending troponins and inflammatory markers Hemoglobin stable able to eat and drink Discharged home on protonix and carafate on 12/30/21 Ultimately diagnosed with EBV and hyperinflammatory state. No Misc given self resolving fever and downtrending inflammation without treatement. No myocarditis given normal echo, ekgs, and normal cardiac MRI. It was felt that the elevated troponins were due to cross reactivity with EBV.

text: This 41 year old female reported receipt of her primary DRYVAX on 25 June 2003. Three AVA vaccinations were administered on 06 Sept 2003, 22 Sept 2003, and 11 Oct 2003 with no remembered adverse events to either vaccine. During a routine physical 14 Nov 2003 (1 month post 3rd AVA vac), a CBC identified "mild microcytic anemia" (WBC 5.2 (nl), High 12; HCT 37 MCV 85; neut 47%; lymph 47%) otherwise normal). She admitted to being tired and a family history of hypothyroidism otherwise no complaints documented or remembered. Providers suggested diagnosis of "high probability thalassemia". On 20 June 2004 ( months post vaccination) she complain of 2 day hx of itchy scalp with tender scalp and hair loss (hx of similar hair loss at age 9-10), headaches (hx tension ha), increased fatigue, and cervical-aural lymphadenopathy. She was diagnosed with superficial cellulitis and given KEFLEX. F/u eval 6/28/04 dx tinea capitis (positive woods lamp) and given griseofulvin and selenium sulfide shampoo. By 7/3/04 her symptoms had not changed and she now reported fever of 102 F with night sweats. She was treated with ROCEPHIN 1 gm IM X 3 days. By 7/9/04 the lymphadenopathy was resolving; however she exhibited a new vesicular papular itchy rash to bilateral arms, face and oral thrush with a sore throat-diagnosed with possible allergic reaction to griseofulvin. Meds were stopped and she was treated with 7 day taper of Prednisone and given DIFLUCAN with resolution of symptoms except alopecia. While hair regrowth did occur, new sites would develop, dermatology referral:  2 punch biopsies showed "inflammatory scarring alopecia with features consistent with lupus erythematosus. Negative GMS fungal stain". She was diagnosed with discoid lupus 18 August 2004 and referred to internal medicine doe SLE. October 2004 (12 months post AVA#3 vac) repetitive monthly flare ups of alopecia, fevers, arthralgia was associated with onset of menstrual cycles. She was admitted by rheumatology October 6-12, 2004 with neutropenic fever (ANC 325 and c/o 2 week hx fevers>102F, chills, HA, fatigue, sore throat, mouth ulcers, arthralgia, chronic LBP). Symptoms resolved with supportive therapy. Features were noted to be suggestive of SLE or DLE converting to SLE with negative ANA, cytopenia, fever, adenopathy, arthralgia, and fatigue (see below labs). Rheumatology diagnosed ANA-negative SLE based on DLE lesions and organ symptomatology (cytopenia from 2004 to present day, she continues to be followed by rheumatology, PCP, dermatology, GYN, et at for re-flare of symptoms.  Follow-up - Patient's last name updated.

text: This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of burning sensation in a 67-year-old female patient who received SHINGRIX for prophylaxis. On 29th August 2018, the patient received the 1st dose of SHINGRIX (intramuscular). On an unknown date, less than a week after receiving SHINGRIX, the patient experienced burning sensation, weakness, sickness, headache, increased skin sensitivity, feeling cold and fever. On an unknown date, the outcome of the burning sensation, weakness, headache, increased skin sensitivity, feeling cold and fever were unknown and the outcome of the sickness was recovered/resolved. It was unknown if the reporter considered the burning sensation, weakness, sickness, headache, increased skin sensitivity, feeling cold and fever to be related to SHINGRIX. Additional details were provided as follows: The patient developed a fever and headache initially. The patient at the time of reporting described that she got a burning sensation in her hands that comes and goes. She had cold sensations and nerve sensations in her legs. She felt weak and she no longer had the harmonious hum in her brain that she had prior to the vaccination. The patient said that she had been sick for six days. The patient had denied permission to contact their physician. The reporter was unable to obtain additional information.
labels: Hyperaesthesia, Headache, Pyrexia, Burning sensation, Asthenia, Feeling cold
